# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gpio-expanders
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] A **general-purpose input/output** (**GPIO**) is an uncommitted digital signal pin on an integrated circuit or electronic circuit (e.g.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] MCUs/MPUs) board that can be used as an input or output, or both, and is controllable by software.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] GPIOs have no predefined purpose and are unused by default.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] If used, the purpose and behavior of a GPIO is defined and implemented by the designer of higher assembly-level circuitry: the circuit board designer in the case of integrated circuit GPIOs, or system integrator in the case of board-level GPIOs.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] Integrated circuit (IC) GPIOs are implemented in a variety of ways.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] Some ICs provide GPIOs as a primary function whereas others include GPIOs as a convenient "accessory" to some other primary function.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] Examples of the former include the Intel 8255, which interfaces 24 GPIOs to a parallel communication bus, and various GPIO *expander* ICs, which interface GPIOs to serial communication buses such as I²C and SMBus.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] An example of the latter is the Realtek ALC260 IC, which provides eight GPIOs along with its main function of audio codec.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] Microcontroller ICs usually include GPIOs.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] Depending on the application, a microcontroller's GPIOs may comprise its primary interface to external circuitry or they may be just one type of I/O used among several, such as analog signal I/O, counter/timer, and serial communication.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] In some ICs, particularly microcontrollers, a GPIO pin may be capable of other functions than GPIO.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] Often in such cases it is necessary to configure the pin to operate as a GPIO (vis-à-vis its other functions) in addition to configuring the GPIO's behavior.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] Some microcontroller devices (e.g., Microchip dsPIC33 family) incorporate internal signal routing circuitry that allows GPIOs to be programmatically mapped to device pins.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] Field-programmable gate arrays (FPGA) extend this ability by allowing GPIO pin mapping, instantiation and architecture to be programmatically controlled.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] Some microcontrollers and FPGAs allow a device to offload the task of bit-banging the GPIO to a separate device, the programmable input/output controller.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] Many circuit boards expose board-level GPIOs to external circuitry through integrated electrical connectors.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] Usually, each such GPIO is accessible via a dedicated connector pin.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] Like IC-based GPIOs, some boards merely include GPIOs as a convenient, auxiliary resource that augments the board's primary function, whereas in other boards the GPIOs are the central, primary function of the board.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] Some boards, which are classified usually as multi-function I/O boards, are a combination of both; such boards provide GPIOs along with other types of general-purpose I/O.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] GPIOs are also found on embedded controller boards and Single board computers such as Arduino, BeagleBone, and Raspberry Pi.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] While some board-level GPIOs are simple connections to IC pins, many are given abilities which IC-based GPIOs usually lack.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] For example, Schmitt-trigger inputs, high-current output drivers, optical isolators, or combinations of these, may be used to buffer and condition the GPIO signals and to protect board circuitry.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] Also, higher-level functions are sometimes implemented, such as input debounce, input signal edge detection, and pulse-width modulation (PWM) output.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] GPIOs are used in a diverse variety of applications, limited only by the electrical and timing specifications of the GPIO interface and the ability of software to interact with GPIOs in a sufficiently timely manner.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] GPIOs usually employ standard logic levels and cannot supply significant current to output loads.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] When followed by an appropriate high-current output buffer (or mechanical or solid-state relay), a GPIO may be used to control high-power devices such as lights, solenoids, heaters, and motors (e.g., fans and blowers).
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] Similarly, an input buffer, relay or opto-isolator is often used to translate an otherwise incompatible signal (e.g., high voltage) to the logic levels required by a GPIO.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] Integrated circuit GPIOs are commonly used to control or monitor other circuitry (including other ICs) on a board.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] Examples of this include enabling and disabling the operation of (or power to) other circuitry, reading the states of on-board switches and configuration shunts, and driving light-emitting diode (LED) status indicators.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] In the latter case, a GPIO can, in many cases, supply enough output current to directly power an LED without using an intermediate buffer.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] Multiple GPIOs are sometimes used together as a bit banging communication interface.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] Taken to the extreme, this method may be used to implement an entire parallel bus, thus allowing communication with bus-oriented ICs or circuit boards.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] Although GPIOs are fundamentally digital in nature, they are often used to control analog processes.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] For example, a GPIO may be used to control motor speed, light intensity, or temperature.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] Usually, this is done via PWM, in which the duty cycle of the GPIO output signal determines the effective magnitude of the process control signal.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] For example, when controlling light intensity, the light may be dimmed by reducing the GPIO duty cycle.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] Some analog processes require an analog control voltage.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] In such cases, it may be feasible to connect a GPIO, which is operated as a PWM output, to an RC filter to create a simple, low cost digital-to-analog converter.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] In some cases, they are simple—a group of pins that can switch as a group to either input or output.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] In others, each pin can be set up to accept or source different logic voltages, with configurable drive strengths and pull ups/downs.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] Input and output voltages are usually, but not always, limited to the supply voltage of the device with the GPIOs, and may be damaged by greater voltages.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] A GPIO pin's state may be exposed to the software developer through one of a number of different interfaces, such as a memory-mapped I/O peripheral, or through dedicated IO port instructions.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] Some GPIOs have 5 V tolerant inputs: even when the device has a low supply voltage (such as 2 V), the device can accept 5 V without damage.
[src:gpio-expanders/general-purpose-input-output] A GPIO port is a group of GPIO pins (often 8 pins, but it may be fewer) arranged in a group and controlled as a group.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The I2C bus can be found in a wide range of electronics applications where simplicity and low manufacturing cost are more important than speed.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] PC components and systems which involve I2C include serial presence detect (SPD) EEPROMs on dual in-line memory modules (DIMMs) and Extended Display Identification Data (EDID) for monitors via VGA, DVI, and HDMI connectors.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] A particular strength of I2C is the capability of a microcontroller to control a network of device chips with just two general-purpose I/O pins.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Many other bus technologies used in similar applications, such as Serial Peripheral Interface Bus (SPI), require more pins and signals to connect multiple devices.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] System Management Bus (SMBus), defined by Intel and Duracell in 1994, is a subset of I2C, defining a stricter usage.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] One purpose of SMBus is to promote robustness and interoperability.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Accordingly, modern I2C systems incorporate some policies and rules from SMBus, sometimes supporting both I2C and SMBus, requiring only minimal reconfiguration either by commanding or output pin use.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] System management for PC systems uses SMBus, whose pins are allocated in both conventional PCI and PCI Express connectors.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] In the European Patent EP0051332B1 Ad P.M.M.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Moelands and Herman Schutte are named as inventors of the I2C bus.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Both were working in 1980 as development engineers in the central application laboratory CAB of Philips in Eindhoven, where the I2C bus was developed as "Two-wire bus-system comprising a clock wire and a data wire for interconnecting a number of stations".
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The US patent was granted under number US 4689740A .
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The internal development name of the bus was first COMIC, which was later changed to I2C.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The patent was transferred to Koninklijke Philips NV.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] I2C patents and specifications used the terms *master/slave* between 1980 and 2021.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] In 2021, revision 7 of the I2C specification changed the terms to *controller/target*.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The technical definitions of such devices, and their roles on an I2C bus, remain unchanged.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] I2C uses only two signals: serial data line (SDA) and serial clock line (SCL).
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Both are bidirectional and pulled up with resistors.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Typical voltages used are +5 V or +3.3 V, although systems with other voltages are permitted.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The I2C reference design has a 7-bit address space, with a rarely used 10-bit extension.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Some vendors report 8-bit and 11-bit addresses instead, as the lowest bit in the first address byte is used to differentiate between write and read commands.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Common I2C bus speeds are the 100 kbit/s *standard mode* and the 400 kbit/s *fast mode*.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] There is also a 10 kbit/s *low-speed mode*, but arbitrarily low clock frequencies are also allowed.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Later revisions of I2C can host more nodes and run at faster speeds (400 kbit/s *fast mode*, 1 Mbit/s *fast mode plus*, 3.4 Mbit/s *high-speed mode*, and 5 Mbit/s *ultra-fast mode*).
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] These speeds are more widely used on embedded systems than on PCs.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Note that the bit rates are quoted for the transfers between controller (master) and target (slave) without clock stretching or other hardware overhead.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Protocol overheads include a target address and perhaps a register address within the target device, as well as per-byte ACK/NACK bits.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Thus the actual transfer rate of user data is lower than those peak bit rates alone would imply.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] For example, if each interaction with a target inefficiently allows only 1 byte of data to be transferred, the data rate will be less than half the peak bit rate.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The number of nodes that can exist on a given I2C bus is limited by the address space and also by the total bus capacitance of 400 pF, which restricts practical communication distances to a few meters.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The relatively high impedance and low noise immunity require a common ground potential, which again restricts practical use to communication within the same PC board or small system of boards.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The aforementioned reference design is a bus with a clock (SCL) and data (SDA) lines with 7-bit addressing.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The bus is a multi-controller bus, which means that any number of controller nodes can be present.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Additionally, controller and target roles may be changed between messages (after a STOP is sent).
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] In addition to 0 and 1 data bits, the I2C bus allows special START and STOP signals, which act as message delimiters and are distinct from the data bits.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The controller is initially in controller transmit mode by sending a START followed by the 7-bit address of the target it wishes to communicate with, which is finally followed by a single bit representing whether it wishes to write (0) to or read (1) from the target.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] If the target exists on the bus then it will respond with an ACK bit (active low for acknowledged) for that address.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The controller then continues in either transmit or receive mode (according to the read/write bit it sent), and the target continues in the complementary mode (receive or transmit, respectively).
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The address and the data bytes are sent most significant bit first.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The start condition is indicated by a high-to-low transition of SDA with SCL high; the stop condition is indicated by a low-to-high transition of SDA with SCL high.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] All other transitions of SDA take place with SCL low.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] If the controller wishes to write to the target, then it repeatedly sends a byte with the target sending an ACK bit.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] If the controller wishes to read from the target, then it repeatedly receives a byte from the target, the controller sending an ACK bit after every byte except the last one.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] An I2C transaction may consist of multiple messages.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The controller terminates a message with a STOP condition if this is the end of the transaction or it may send another START condition to retain control of the bus for another message (a "combined format" transaction).
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] In a combined transaction, each read or write begins with a START and the target address.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The START conditions after the first are also called *repeated START* bits.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Repeated STARTs are not preceded by STOP conditions, which is how targets know that the next message is part of the same transaction.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Any given target will only respond to certain messages, as specified in its product documentation.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Pure I2C systems support arbitrary message structures.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] SMBus is restricted to nine of those structures, such as *read word N* and *write word N*, involving a single target.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] PMBus extends SMBus with a *Group* protocol, allowing multiple such SMBus transactions to be sent in one combined message.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The terminating STOP indicates when those grouped actions should take effect.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] For example, one PMBus operation might reconfigure three power supplies (using three different I2C target addresses), and their new configurations would take effect at the same time: when they receive that STOP.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] With only a few exceptions, neither I2C nor SMBus define message semantics, such as the meaning of data bytes in messages.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Message semantics are otherwise product-specific.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Those exceptions include messages addressed to the I2C *general call* address (0x00) or to the SMBus *Alert Response Address*; and messages involved in the SMBus *Address Resolution Protocol* (ARP) for dynamic address allocation and management.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] In practice, most targets adopt request-response control models, where one or more bytes following a write command are treated as a command or address.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Those bytes determine how subsequent written bytes are treated or how the target responds on subsequent reads.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Most SMBus operations involve single-byte commands.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] One specific example is the 24C32 type EEPROM, which uses two request bytes that are called Address High and Address Low.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] (Accordingly, these EEPROMs are not usable by pure SMBus hosts, which support only single-byte commands or addresses.) These bytes are used for addressing bytes within the 32 kbit (or 4 kB) EEPROM address space.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The same two-byte addressing is also used by larger EEPROMs, like the 24C512, which stores 512 kbits (or 64 kB).
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Writing data to and reading from these EEPROMs uses a simple protocol: the address is written, and then data is transferred until the end of the message.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The data transfer part of the protocol can cause trouble on the SMBus, since the data bytes are not preceded by a count, and more than 32 bytes can be transferred at once.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] I2C EEPROMs smaller than 32 kbit, like the 2 kbit 24C02, are often used on the SMBus with inefficient single-byte data transfers to overcome this problem.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] After the START, the controller sends the chip's bus address with the direction bit clear (*write*), then sends the two-byte address of data within the EEPROM and then sends data bytes to be written starting at that address, followed by a STOP.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] When writing multiple bytes, all the bytes must be in the same 32-byte page.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] While it is busy saving those bytes to memory, the EEPROM will not respond to further I2C requests.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] To read starting at a particular address in the EEPROM, a combined message is used.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] After a START, the controller first writes that chip's bus address with the direction bit clear (*write*) and then the two bytes of EEPROM data address.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] It then sends a (repeated) START and the EEPROM's bus address with the direction bit set (*read*).
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The EEPROM will then respond with the data bytes beginning at the specified EEPROM data address — a combined message: first a write, then a read.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The controller issues an ACK after each read byte except the last byte, and then issues a STOP.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The EEPROM increments the address after each data byte transferred; multi-byte reads can retrieve the entire contents of the EEPROM using one combined message.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] At the physical layer, both SCL and SDA lines are an open-drain (MOSFET) or open-collector (BJT) bus design, thus a pull-up resistor is needed for each line.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] A logic "0" is output by pulling the line to ground, and a logic "1" is output by letting the line float (output high impedance) so that the pull-up resistor pulls it high.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] This wiring allows multiple nodes to connect to the bus without short circuits from signal contention.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] High-speed systems (and some others) may use a current source instead of a resistor to pull up only SCL or both SCL and SDA, to accommodate higher bus capacitance and enable faster rise times.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] An important consequence of this is that multiple nodes may be driving the lines simultaneously.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] If *any* node is driving the line low, it will be low.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Nodes that are trying to transmit a logical one (i.e., letting the line float high) can detect this and conclude that another node is active at the same time.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] When used on SCL, this is called *clock stretching* and is a flow-control mechanism for targets.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] When used on SDA, this is called arbitration and ensures that there is only one transmitter at a time.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] To start a transaction, SDA is pulled low while SCL remains high.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] It is illegal to transmit a stop marker by releasing SDA to float high again (although such a "void message" is usually harmless), so the next step is to pull SCL low.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Except for the start and stop signals, the SDA line only changes while the clock is low; transmitting a data bit consists of pulsing the clock line high while holding the data line steady at the desired level.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] While SCL is low, the transmitter (initially the controller) sets SDA to the desired value and (after a small delay to let the value propagate) lets SCL float high.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The controller then waits for SCL to actually go high; this will be delayed by the finite rise time of the SCL signal (the RC time constant of the pull-up resistor and the parasitic capacitance of the bus) and may be additionally delayed by a target's clock stretching.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Once SCL is high, the controller waits a minimum time (4 μs for standard-speed I2C) to ensure that the receiver has seen the bit, then pulls it low again.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] After every 8 data bits in one direction, an "acknowledge" bit is transmitted in the other direction.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The transmitter and receiver switch roles for one bit, and the original receiver transmits a single "0" bit (ACK) back.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Only the SDA line changes direction during acknowledge bits; the SCL is always controlled by the controller.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] One of the more significant features of the I2C protocol is clock stretching.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] An addressed target device may hold the clock line (SCL) low after receiving (or sending) a byte, indicating that it is not yet ready to process more data.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The controller that is communicating with the target may not finish the transmission of the current bit, but must wait until the clock line actually goes high.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] If the target is clock-stretching, the clock line will still be low (because the connections are open-drain).
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The same is true if a second, slower, controller tries to drive the clock at the same time.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The controller must wait until it observes the clock line going high, and an additional minimal time (4 μs for standard 100 kbit/s I2C) before pulling the clock low again.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Although the controller may also hold the SCL line low for as long as it desires (this is not allowed since Rev.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] 6 of the protocol – subsection 3.1.1), the term "clock stretching" is normally used only when targets do it.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Although in theory any clock pulse may be stretched, generally it is the intervals before or after the acknowledgment bit that are used.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] For example, if the target is a microcontroller, its I2C interface could stretch the clock after each byte, until the software decides whether to send a positive acknowledgment or a NACK.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Clock stretching is the only time in I2C where the target drives SCL.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Many targets do not need to clock stretch and thus treat SCL as strictly an input with no circuitry to drive it.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Some controllers, such as those found inside custom ASICs, may not support clock stretching; often these devices will be labeled as a "two-wire interface" and not I2C.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] To maximize bus throughput, SMBus places limits on how far clocks may be stretched.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Hosts and targets adhering to those limits cannot block access to the bus for more than a short time, which is not a guarantee made by pure I2C systems.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Every controller monitors the bus for start and stop bits and does not start a message while another controller is keeping the bus busy.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] However, two controllers may start transmission at about the same time; in this case, arbitration occurs.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Target transmit mode can also be arbitrated when a controller addresses multiple targets, but this is less common.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] In contrast to protocols (such as Ethernet) that use random back-off delays before issuing a retry, I2C has a deterministic arbitration policy.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Each transmitter checks the level of the data line (SDA) and compares it with the levels it expects; if they do not match, that transmitter has lost arbitration and drops out of this protocol interaction.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] If one transmitter sets SDA to 1 (not driving a signal) and a second transmitter sets it to 0 (pull to ground), the result is that the line is low.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The first transmitter then observes that the level of the line is different from that expected and concludes that another node is transmitting.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The first node to notice such a difference is the one that loses arbitration: it stops driving SDA.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] If it is a controller, it also stops driving SCL and waits for a STOP; then it may try to reissue its entire message.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] In the meantime, the other node has not noticed any difference between the expected and actual levels on SDA and therefore continues transmission.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] It can do so without problems because so far the signal has been exactly as it expected; no other transmitter has disturbed its message.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] If the two controllers are sending a message to two different targets, the one sending the lower target address always "wins" arbitration in the address stage.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Since the two controllers may send messages to the same target address, and addresses sometimes refer to multiple targets, arbitration must sometimes continue into the data stages.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Arbitration occurs very rarely, but is necessary for proper multi-controller support.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] As with clock stretching, not all devices support arbitration.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Those that do, generally label themselves as supporting "multi-controller" communication.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] One case which must be handled carefully in multi-controller I2C implementations is that of the controllers talking to each other.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] One controller may lose arbitration to an incoming message, and must change its role from controller to target in time to acknowledge its own address.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] In the extremely rare case that two controllers simultaneously send identical messages, both will regard the communication as successful, but the target will only see one message.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] For this reason, when a target can be accessed by multiple controllers, every command recognized by the target either must be idempotent or must be guaranteed never to be issued by two controllers at the same time.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] While I2C only arbitrates between controllers, SMBus uses arbitration in three additional contexts, where multiple targets respond to the controller, and one gets its message through.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] PMBus version 1.3 extends the SMBus alert response protocol in its "zone read" protocol.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Targets may be grouped into "zones", and all targets in a zone may be addressed to respond, with their responses masked (omitting unwanted information), inverted (so wanted information is sent as 0 bits, which win arbitration), or reordered (so the most significant information is sent first).
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Arbitration ensures that the highest priority response is the one first returned to the controller.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] PMBus reserves I2C addresses 0x28 and 0x37 for zone reads and writes, respectively.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] There are several possible operating modes for I2C communication.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] 3. because it identifies the controller (there are eight controller codes, and each controller must use a different one), it ensures that arbitration is complete before the high-speed portion of the transfer, and so the high-speed portion need not make allowances for that ability.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Some of the vendors provide a so-called non-standard *Turbo mode* with a speed up to 1.4 Mbit/s.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] In all modes, the clock frequency is controlled by the controller(s), and a longer-than-normal bus may be operated at a slower-than-nominal speed by underclocking.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] I2C is popular for interfacing peripheral circuits to prototyping systems, such as the Arduino and Raspberry Pi.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] I2C does not employ a standardized connector; however, board designers have created various wiring schemes for I2C interconnections.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] To minimize the possible damage due to plugging 0.1-inch headers in backwards, some developers have suggested using alternating signal and power connections of the following wiring schemes: (GND, SCL, VCC, SDA) or (VCC, SDA, GND, SCL).
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The vast majority of applications use I2C in the way it was originally designed—peripheral ICs directly wired to a processor on the same printed circuit board, and therefore over relatively short distances of less than 1 foot (30 cm), without a connector.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] However using a differential driver, an alternate version of I2C can communicate up to 20 meters (possibly over 100 meters) over CAT5 or other cable.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Several standard connectors carry I2C signals.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] For example, the UEXT, the 10-pin iPack, and the 6P6C Lego Mindstorms NXT connectors carry I2C.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Every HDMI and most DVI and VGA connectors carry DDC2 data over I2C.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Additionally, 8P8C connectors and a CAT5 cable normally used for the Ethernet physical layer can sometimes be used to carry differential-encoded or boosted single-ended I2C signals.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] When there are many I2C devices in a system, there can be a need to include bus buffers or multiplexers to split large bus segments into smaller ones.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] This can be necessary to keep the capacitance of a bus segment below the allowable value or to allow multiple devices with the same address to be separated by a multiplexer.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Many types of multiplexers and buffers exist and all must take into account the fact that I2C lines are specified to be bidirectional.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Multiplexers can be implemented with analog switches, which can tie one segment to another.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Analog switches maintain the bidirectional nature of the lines but do not isolate the capacitance of one segment from another or provide buffering capability.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Buffers can be used to isolate capacitance on one segment from another and/or allow I2C to be sent over longer cables or traces.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Buffers for bi-directional lines such as I2C must use one of several schemes for preventing latch-up.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] I2C is open-drain, so buffers must drive a low on one side when they see a low on the other.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] One method for preventing latch-up is for a buffer to have carefully selected input and output levels such that the output level of its driver is higher than its input threshold, preventing it from triggering itself.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] For example, a buffer may have an input threshold of 0.4 V for detecting a low, but an output low level of 0.5 V.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] This method requires that all other devices on the bus have thresholds which are compatible and often means that multiple buffers implementing this scheme cannot be put in series with one another.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Alternatively, other types of buffers exist that implement current amplifiers or keep track of the state (i.e., which side drove the bus low) to prevent latch-up.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The state method typically means that an unintended pulse is created during a hand-off when one side is driving the bus low, then the other drives it low, then the first side releases (this is common during an I2C acknowledgement).
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] When having a single controller, it is possible to have multiple I2C buses share the same SCL line.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The packets on each bus are either sent one after the other or at the same time.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] This is possible because the communication on each bus can be subdivided into alternating short periods with high SCL followed by short periods with low SCL.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] And the clock can be stretched if one bus needs more time in one state.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Advantages are using target devices with the same address at the same time and saving connections or a faster throughput by using several data lines at the same time.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] These tables show the various atomic states and bit operations that may occur during an I2C message.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] In addition, the remaining 112 addresses are designated for specific classes of devices, and some of them are further reserved by either related standards or common usage.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] SMBus reserves some additional addresses.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Although MSB `1111` is reserved for Device ID and 10-bit target (slave) addressing, it is also used by VESA DDC display dependent devices such as pointing devices.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] An I2C *transaction* consists of one or more *messages*.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Each message begins with a start symbol, and the transaction ends with a stop symbol.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Start symbols after the first, which begin a message but not a transaction, are referred to as *repeated start* symbols.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] A transaction consisting of a single message is called either a read or a write transaction.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] A transaction consisting of multiple messages is called a combined transaction.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The most common form of the latter is a write message providing intra-device address information, followed by a read message.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Many I2C devices do not distinguish between a combined transaction and the same messages sent as separate transactions, but not all.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The device ID protocol requires a single transaction; targets are forbidden from responding if they observe a stop symbol.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Configuration, calibration or self-test modes that cause the target to respond unusually are also often automatically terminated at the end of a transaction.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] SCL is pulled low, and SDA sets the first data bit level while keeping SCL low (during blue bar time).
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The data is sampled (received) when SCL rises for the first bit (B1).
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] For a bit to be valid, SDA must not change between a rising edge of SCL and the subsequent falling edge (the entire green bar time).
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] This process repeats, SDA transitioning while SCL is low, and the data being read while SCL is high (B2 through Bn).
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The final bit is followed by a clock pulse, during which SDA is pulled low in preparation for the *stop* bit.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] A *stop* condition (P) is signalled when SCL rises, followed by SDA rising.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] To avoid false marker detection, there is a minimum delay between the SCL falling edge and changing SDA, and between changing SDA and the SCL rising edge.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The minimum delay time is dependent upon the data transfer rate in use.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Note that an I2C message containing n data bits (including acknowledgements) contains *n* + 1 clock pulses.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] I2C lends itself to a "bus driver" software design.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Software for attached devices is written to call a "bus driver" that handles the actual low-level I2C hardware.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] This permits the driver code for attached devices to port easily to other hardware, including a bit-banging design.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] When developing or troubleshooting systems using I2C, visibility at the level of hardware signals can be important.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] There are a number of I2C host adapter hardware solutions for making an I2C controller or target connection to host computers, running Linux, Mac or Windows.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Not all of them require proprietary drivers or APIs.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] I2C protocol analyzers are tools that sample an I2C bus and decode the electrical signals to provide a higher-level view of the data being transmitted on the bus.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] When developing and/or troubleshooting the I2C bus, examination of hardware signals can be very important.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Logic analyzers are tools that collect, analyze, decode, and store signals, so people can view the high-speed waveforms at their leisure.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Logic analyzers display time stamps of each signal level change, which can help find protocol problems.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Most logic analyzers have the capability to decode bus signals into high-level protocol data and show ASCII data.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The assignment of target addresses is a weakness of I2C.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Seven bits are too few to prevent address collisions between the many thousands of available devices.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] What alleviates the issue of address collisions between different vendors and also allows connecting to several identical devices is that manufacturers dedicate pins that can be used to set the target address to one of a few address options per device.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Two or three pins is typical, and with many devices, there are three or more wiring options per address pin.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] 10-bit I2C addresses are not yet widely used, and many host operating systems do not support them.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Neither is the complex SMBus "ARP" scheme for dynamically assigning addresses (other than for PCI cards with SMBus presence, for which it is required).
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Automatic bus configuration is a related issue.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] A given address may be used by a number of different protocol-incompatible devices in various systems, and hardly any device types can be detected at runtime.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] For example, `0x51` may be used by a 24LC02 or 24C32 EEPROM, with incompatible addressing; or by a PCF8563 RTC, which cannot reliably be distinguished from either (without changing device state, which might not be allowed).
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The only reliable configuration mechanisms available to hosts involve out-of-band mechanisms such as tables provided by system firmware, which list the available devices.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Again, this issue can partially be addressed by ARP in SMBus systems, especially when vendor and product identifiers are used, but that has not really caught on.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] 3 version of the I2C specification adds a device ID mechanism.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Hosts supporting the multi-megabit speeds are rare.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Support for the Fm+ 1 Mbit/s speed is more widespread, since its electronics are simple variants of what is used at lower speeds.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Many devices do not support the 400 kbit/s speed (in part because SMBus does not yet support it).
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] I2C nodes implemented in software (instead of dedicated hardware) may not even support the 100 kbit/s speed; so the whole range defined in the specification is rarely usable.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] All devices must at least partially support the highest speed used or they may spuriously detect their device address.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Devices are allowed to stretch clock cycles to suit their particular needs, which can starve bandwidth needed by faster devices and increase latencies when talking to other device addresses.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Bus capacitance also places a limit on the transfer speed, especially when current sources are not used to decrease signal rise times.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Because I2C is a shared bus, there is the potential for any device to have a fault and hang the entire bus.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] For example, if any device holds the SDA or SCL line low, it prevents the controller from sending START or STOP commands to reset the bus.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Thus it is common for designs to include a reset signal that provides an external method of resetting the bus devices.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] However, many devices do not have a dedicated reset pin, forcing the designer to put in circuitry to allow devices to be power-cycled if they need to be reset.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Because of these limits (address management, bus configuration, potential faults, speed), few I2C bus segments have even a dozen devices.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Instead, it is common for systems to have several smaller segments.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] One might be dedicated to use with high-speed devices for low-latency power management.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Another might be used to control a few devices where latency and throughput are not important issues; yet another segment might be used only to read EEPROM chips describing add-on cards (such as the SPD standard used with DRAM sticks).
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] On very low-power systems, the pull-up resistors can use more power than the entire rest of the design combined.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] On these, the resistors are often powered by a switchable voltage source, such as a DIO from a microcontroller.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] The pull-ups also limit the speed of the bus and have a small additional cost.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p01] Therefore, some designers are turning to other serial buses that do not need pull-ups, such as I3C or SPI.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p02] I2C is the basis for the ACCESS.bus, the VESA Display Data Channel (DDC) interface, the System Management Bus (SMBus), Power Management Bus (PMBus) and the Intelligent Platform Management Bus (IPMB, one of the protocols of IPMI).
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p02] These variants have differences in voltage and clock frequency ranges, and may have interrupt lines.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p02] High-availability systems (AdvancedTCA, MicroTCA) use 2-way redundant I2C for shelf management.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p02] Multi-controller I2C capability is a requirement in these systems.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p02] TWI (Two-Wire Interface) or TWSI (Two-Wire Serial Interface) is essentially the same bus implemented on various system-on-chip processors from Atmel and other vendors.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p02] Vendors use the name TWI, even though I2C is not a registered trademark as of 2014-11-07.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p02] Trademark protection only exists for the respective logo (see upper right corner), and patents on I2C have now lapsed.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p02] According to Microchip Technology, TWI and I2C have a few differences.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p02] One of them is that TWI does not support START byte.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p02] In some cases, use of the term "two-wire interface" indicates incomplete implementation of the I2C specification.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p02] Not supporting arbitration or clock stretching is one common limitation, which is still useful for a single controller communicating with simple targets that never stretch the clock.
[src:gpio-expanders/i²c-p02] MIPI I3C sensor interface standard (I3C) is a development of I2C, under development in 2017.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] SPI follows a master–slave architecture, where a device (variously called master, leader, controller, main...) orchestrates communication with one or more devices (variously called slave, follower, target, sub...) by driving the clock and chip select signals.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] As there is no formal standard, some manufacturers introduce devices with the ability to change their roles on the fly.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Motorola's original specification (from the early 1980s) uses four logic signals, aka lines or wires, to support full duplex communication.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] It is sometimes called a *four-wire* serial bus to contrast with three-wire variants which are half duplex, and with the *two-wire* I²C and 1-Wire serial buses.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Typical applications include interfacing microcontrollers with peripheral chips for Secure Digital cards, liquid crystal displays, analog-to-digital and digital-to-analog converters, flash and EEPROM memory, and various communication chips.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Although SPI is a synchronous serial interface, it is different from Synchronous Serial Interface (SSI).
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] SSI employs differential signaling and provides only a single simplex communication channel.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Variations may use different names or have different signals.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] MOSI on a master outputs to MOSI on a slave.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] MISO on a slave outputs to MISO on a master.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Each device internally uses a shift register for serial communication, which together forms an inter-chip circular buffer.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] To support multidrop bus, slave devices should use tri-state outputs so their MISO signal becomes high impedance (electrically disconnected) when the device is not selected.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Slaves without tri-state outputs cannot share a MISO line with other slaves without using an external tri-state buffer.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] To begin communication, the SPI master first selects the device it wants to communicate with by pulling its SS low.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] If a waiting period is required, such as for an analog-to-digital conversion, the master must wait for at least that period of time before issuing clock cycles.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] During each SPI clock cycle, full-duplex transmission of a single bit occurs.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] The master sends a bit on the MOSI line while the slave sends a bit on the MISO line, and then each reads their corresponding incoming bit.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] This sequence is maintained even when only one-directional data transfer is intended.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Transmission using a single slave involves one shift register in the master and one shift register in the slave, both of some given word size (e.g.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] The transmissions often consist of eight-bit words, but other word-sizes are also common, for example, sixteen-bit words for touch-screen controllers or audio codecs, such as the TSC2101 by Texas Instruments, or twelve-bit words for many digital-to-analog or analog-to-digital converters.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Data is usually shifted out with the most-significant bit (MSB) first but the original specification has a LSBFE ("LSB-First Enable") to control whether data is transferred least (LSB) or most significant bit (MSB) first.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] On the clock edge, both master and slave shift out a bit to its counterpart.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] On the next clock edge, each receiver samples the transmitted bit and stores it in the shift register as the new least-significant bit.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] After all bits have been shifted out and in, the master and slave have exchanged register values.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] If more data needs to be exchanged, the shift registers are reloaded and the process repeats.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Transmission may continue for any number of clock cycles.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] When complete, the master stops toggling the clock signal, and typically deselects the slave.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] If a single slave device is used, its SS pin *may* be fixed to logic low if the slave permits it.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] With multiple slave devices, a multidrop configuration requires an independent SS signal from the master for each slave device, while a daisy-chain configuration only requires one SS signal.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Every slave on the bus that has not been selected should disregard the input clock and MOSI signals.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] And to prevent contention on MISO, non-selected slaves must use tristate output.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Slaves that are not already tristate will need external tristate buffers to ensure this.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] In addition to setting the clock frequency, the master must also configure the clock polarity and phase with respect to the data.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Motorola named these two options as CPOL and CPHA (for **c**lock **pol**arity and **c**lock **pha**se) respectively, a convention most vendors have also adopted.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Some slave devices are designed to ignore any SPI communications in which the number of clock pulses is greater than specified.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Others do not care, ignoring extra inputs and continuing to shift the same output bit.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Interrupts are outside the scope of SPI; their usage is neither forbidden nor specified, and so may be implemented optionally.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Microcontrollers configured as slave devices may have hardware support for generating interrupt signals to themselves when data words are received or overflow occurs in a receive FIFO buffer, and may also set up an interrupt routine when their slave select input line is pulled low or high.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] SPI slaves sometimes use an out-of-band signal (another wire) to send an interrupt signal to a master.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Examples include pen-down interrupts from touchscreen sensors, thermal limit alerts from temperature sensors, alarms issued by real-time clock chips, SDIO and audio jack insertions for an audio codec.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Interrupts to master may also be faked by using polling (similarly to USB 1.1 and 2.0).
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Though the previous operation section focused on a basic interface with a single slave, SPI can instead communicate with multiple slaves using multidrop, daisy chain, or expander configurations.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] In the multidrop bus configuration, each slave has its own SS, and the master selects only one at a time.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] MISO, SCLK, and MOSI are each shared by all devices.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Since the MISO pins of the slaves are connected together, they are required to be tri-state pins (high, low or high-impedance), where the high-impedance output must be applied when the slave is not selected.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Slave devices not supporting tri-state may be used in multidrop configuration by adding a tri-state buffer chip controlled by its SS signal.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Some products that implement SPI may be connected in a daisy chain configuration, where the first slave's output is connected to the second slave's input, and so on with subsequent slaves, until the final slave, whose output is connected back to the master's input.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] This effectively merges the individual communication shift registers of each slave to form a single larger combined shift register that shifts data through the chain.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] This configuration only requires a single SS line from the master, rather than a separate SS line for each slave.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] In addition to using SPI-specific slaves, daisy-chained SPI can include discrete shift registers for more pins of inputs (e.g. using the parallel-in serial-out 74xx165) or outputs (e.g. using the serial-in parallel-out 74xx595) chained indefinitely.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Other applications that can potentially interoperate with daisy-chained SPI include SGPIO, JTAG, and I2C.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Expander configurations use SPI-controlled addressing units (e.g. binary decoders, demultiplexers, or shift registers) to add chip selects.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] For example, one SS can be used for transmitting to a SPI-controlled demultiplexer an index number controlling its select signals, while another SS is routed through that demultiplexer according to that index to select the desired slave.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Board real estate and wiring savings compared to a parallel bus are significant, and have earned SPI a solid role in embedded systems.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] That is true for most system-on-a-chip processors, both with higher-end 32-bit processors such as those using ARM, MIPS, or PowerPC and with lower-end microcontrollers such as the AVR, PIC, and MSP430.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] These chips usually include SPI controllers capable of running in either master or slave mode.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] In-system programmable AVR controllers (including blank ones) can be programmed using SPI.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Chip or FPGA based designs sometimes use SPI to communicate between internal components; on-chip real estate can be as costly as its on-board cousin.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] And for high-performance systems, FPGAs sometimes use SPI to interface as a slave to a host, as a master to sensors, or for flash memory used to bootstrap if they are SRAM-based.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] The full-duplex capability makes SPI very simple and efficient for single master/single slave applications.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Some devices use the full-duplex mode to implement an efficient, swift data stream for applications such as digital audio, digital signal processing, or telecommunications channels, but most off-the-shelf chips stick to half-duplex request/response protocols.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] SPI implementations have a wide variety of protocol variations.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Some devices are transmit-only; others are receive-only.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Slave selects are sometimes active-high rather than active-low.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Some devices send the least-significant bit first.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Signal levels depend entirely on the chips involved.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] And while the baseline SPI protocol has no command codes, every device may define its own protocol of command codes.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Some variations are minor or informal, while others have an official defining document and may be considered to be separate but related protocols.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Motorola in 1983 listed three 6805 8-bit microcomputers that have an integrated "Serial Peripheral Interface", whose functionality is described in a 1984 manual.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Motorola's 1987 Application Node AN991 "Using the Serial Peripheral Interface to Communicate Between Multiple Microcomputers" (now under NXP, last revised 2002) informally serves as the "official" defining document for SPI.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Some devices have timing variations from Motorola's CPOL/CPHA modes.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Sending data from slave to master may use the opposite clock edge as master to slave.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Devices often require extra clock idle time before the first clock or after the last one, or between a command and its response.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Some devices have two clocks, one to read data, and another to transmit it into the device.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Many of the read clocks run from the slave select line.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Different transmission word sizes are common.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Many SPI chips only support messages that are multiples of 8 bits.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Such chips can not interoperate with the JTAG or SGPIO protocols, or any other protocol that requires messages that are not multiples of 8 bits.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Some devices do not use slave select, and instead manage protocol state machine entry/exit using other methods.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Anyone needing an external connector for SPI defines their own or uses another standard connection such as: UEXT, Pmod, various JTAG connectors, Secure Digital card socket, etc.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Some devices require an additional flow control signal from slave to master, indicating when data is ready.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] This leads to a 5-wire protocol instead of the usual 4.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Such a *ready* or *enable* signal is often active-low, and needs to be enabled at key points such as after commands or between words.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Without such a signal, data transfer rates may need to be slowed down significantly, or protocols may need to have dummy bytes inserted, to accommodate the worst case for the slave response time.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Examples include initiating an ADC conversion, addressing the right page of flash memory, and processing enough of a command that device firmware can load the first word of the response.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] SafeSPI is an industry standard for SPI in automotive applications.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Its main focus is the transmission of sensor data between different devices.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] In electrically noisy environments, since SPI has few signals, it can be economical to reduce the effects of common mode noise by adapting SPI to use low-voltage differential signaling.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Another advantage is that the controlled devices can be designed to loop-back to test signal integrity.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] A **Queued Serial Peripheral Interface** (**QSPI**; different to but has same abbreviation as *Quad SPI* described in § Quad SPI) is a type of SPI controller that uses a data queue to transfer data across an SPI bus.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] It has a wrap-around mode allowing continuous transfers to and from the queue with only intermittent attention from the CPU.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Consequently, the peripherals appear to the CPU as memory-mapped parallel devices.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] This feature is useful in applications such as control of an A/D converter.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Other programmable features in Queued SPI are chip selects and transfer length/delay.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] SPI controllers from different vendors support different feature sets; such direct memory access (DMA) queues are not uncommon, although they may be associated with separate DMA engines rather than the SPI controller itself, such as used by **Multichannel Buffered Serial Port** (**MCBSP**).
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Most SPI master controllers integrate support for up to four slave selects, although some require slave selects to be managed separately through GPIO lines.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Note that *Queued SPI* is different from *Quad SPI*, and some processors even confusingly allow a single "QSPI" interface to operate in either quad or queued mode!
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Three-wire variants of SPI restricted to a half-duplex mode use a single bidirectional data line called SISO (slave out/slave in) or MOMI (master out/master in) instead of SPI's two unidirectional lines (MOSI and MISO).
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Three-wire tends to be used for lower-performance parts, such as small EEPROMs used only during system startup, certain sensors, and Microwire.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Few SPI controllers support this mode, although it can be easily bit-banged in software.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] For instances where the full-duplex nature of SPI is not used, an extension uses both data pins in a half-duplex configuration to send two bits per clock cycle.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Typically a command byte is sent requesting a response in dual mode, after which the MOSI line becomes SIO0 (serial I/O 0) and carries even bits, while the MISO line becomes SIO1 and carries odd bits.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Data is still transmitted most-significant bit first, but SIO1 carries bits 7, 5, 3 and 1 of each byte, while SIO0 carries bits 6, 4, 2 and 0.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Further extending quad SPI, some devices support a "quad everything" mode where *all* communication takes place over 4 data lines, including commands.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] This requires programming a configuration bit in the device and requires care after reset to establish communication.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] In addition to using multiple lines for I/O, some devices increase the transfer rate by using double data rate transmission.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] SGPIO is essentially another (incompatible) application stack for SPI designed for particular backplane management activities.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Intel has developed a successor to its Low Pin Count (LPC) bus that it calls the **Enhanced Serial Peripheral Interface** (**eSPI**) bus.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] An eSPI bus can either be shared with SPI devices to save pins or be separate from an SPI bus to allow more performance, especially when eSPI devices need to use SPI flash devices.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] This standard defines an Alert# signal that is used by an eSPI slave to request service from the master.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Only after all of the devices are serviced will the Alert# signal be pulled high due to none of the eSPI slaves needing service and therefore pulling the Alert# signal low.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] This standard allows designers to use 1-bit, 2-bit, or 4-bit communications at speeds from 20 to 66 MHz to further allow designers to trade off performance and cost.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Communications that were out-of-band of LPC like general-purpose input/output (GPIO) and System Management Bus (SMBus) should be tunneled through eSPI via virtual wire cycles and out-of-band message cycles respectively in order to remove those pins from motherboard designs using eSPI.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] This standard supports standard memory cycles with lengths of 1 byte to 4 kilobytes of data, short memory cycles with lengths of 1, 2, or 4 bytes that have much less overhead compared to standard memory cycles, and I/O cycles with lengths of 1, 2, or 4 bytes of data which are low overhead as well.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] This significantly reduces overhead compared to the LPC bus, where all cycles except for the 128-byte firmware hub read cycle spends more than one-half of all of the bus's throughput and time in overhead.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] The standard memory cycle allows a length of anywhere from 1 byte to 4 kilobytes in order to allow its larger overhead to be amortised over a large transaction. eSPI slaves are allowed to initiate bus master versions of all of the memory cycles.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Bus master I/O cycles, which were introduced by the LPC bus specification, and ISA-style DMA including the 32-bit variant introduced by the LPC bus specification, are not present in eSPI.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Therefore, bus master memory cycles are the only allowed DMA in this standard.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] eSPI slaves are allowed to use the eSPI master as a proxy to perform flash operations on a standard SPI flash memory slave on behalf of the requesting eSPI slave.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] 64-bit memory addressing is also added, but is only permitted when there is no equivalent 32-bit address.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] The Intel Z170 chipset can be configured to implement either this bus or a variant of the LPC bus that is missing its ISA-style DMA capability and is underclocked to 24 MHz instead of the standard 33 MHz.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] The eSPI bus is also adopted by AMD Ryzen chipsets.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Microwire, often spelled **μWire**, is essentially a predecessor of SPI and a trademark of National Semiconductor.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] It's a strict subset of SPI: half-duplex, and using SPI mode 0.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Microwire chips tend to need slower clock rates than newer SPI versions; perhaps 2 MHz vs.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Some Microwire chips also support a three-wire mode.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Microwire/Plus is an enhancement of Microwire and features full-duplex communication and support for SPI modes 0 and 1.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] There was no specified improvement in serial clock speed.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Although there are some similarities between SPI and the JTAG (IEEE 1149.1-2013) protocol, they are not interchangeable.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] JTAG is specifically intended to provide reliable test access to the I/O pins from an off-board controller with less precise signal delay and skew parameters, while SPI has many varied applications.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] While not strictly a level sensitive interface, the JTAG protocol supports the recovery of both setup and hold violations between JTAG devices by reducing the clock rate or changing the clock's duty cycles.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Consequently, the JTAG interface is not intended to support extremely high data rates.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Single-board computers may provide pin access to SPI hardware units.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] For instance, the Raspberry Pi's J8 header exposes at least two SPI units that can be used via Linux drivers or python.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] There are a number of USB adapters that allow a desktop PC or smartphone with USB to communicate with SPI chips (e.g.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] They are used for embedded systems, chips (FPGA, ASIC, and SoC) and peripheral testing, programming and debugging.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Many of them also provide scripting or programming capabilities (e.g.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Visual Basic, C/C++, VHDL) and can be used with open source programs like flashrom, IMSProg, SNANDer or avrdude for flash, EEPROM, bootloader and BIOS programming.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] The key SPI parameters are: the maximum supported frequency for the serial interface, command-to-command latency, and the maximum length for SPI commands.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] It is possible to find SPI adapters on the market today that support up to 100 MHz serial interfaces, with virtually unlimited access length.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] SPI protocol being a de facto standard, some SPI host adapters also have the ability of supporting other protocols beyond the traditional 4-wire SPI (for example, support of quad-SPI protocol or other custom serial protocol that derive from SPI).
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Logic analyzers are tools which collect, timestamp, analyze, decode, store, and view the high-speed waveforms, to help debug and develop.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Most logic analyzers have the capability to decode SPI bus signals into high-level protocol data with human-readable labels.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] SPI waveforms can be seen on analog channels (and/or via digital channels in mixed-signal oscilloscopes).
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Most oscilloscope vendors offer optional support for SPI protocol analysis (both 2-, 3-, and 4-wire SPI) with triggering.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Various alternative abbreviations for the four common SPI signals are used.
[src:gpio-expanders/serial-peripheral-interface] Microchip uses *host* and *client* though keeps the abbreviation MOSI and MISO.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] A **shift register** is a type of digital circuit using a cascade of flip-flops where the output of one flip-flop is connected to the input of the next.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] They share a single clock signal, which causes the data stored in the system to shift from one location to the next.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] By connecting the last flip-flop back to the first, the data can cycle within the shifters for extended periods, and in this configuration they were used as computer memory, displacing delay-line memory systems in the late 1960s and early 1970s.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] In most cases, several parallel shift registers would be used to build a larger memory pool known as a "bit array".
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] Data was stored into the array and read back out in parallel, often as a computer word, while each bit was stored serially in the shift registers.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] There is an inherent trade-off in the design of bit arrays; putting more flip-flops in a row allows a single shifter to store more bits, but requires more clock cycles to push the data through all of the shifters before the data can be read back out again.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] Shift registers can have both parallel and serial inputs and outputs.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] These are often configured as "serial-in, parallel-out" (SIPO) or as "parallel-in, serial-out" (PISO).
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] There are also types that have both serial and parallel input and types with serial and parallel output.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] There are also "bidirectional" shift registers, which allow shifting in both directions: L → R or R → L.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] The serial input and serial output of a shift register are connected to create a **circular shift register**.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] A PIPO register (parallel in, parallel out) is simply a D-type register and is *not* a shift register, but is very fast – an output is given within a single clock pulse.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] A "universal" shift register provides bidirectional serial-in and serial-out, as well as parallel-in and parallel-out.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] These are the simplest kind of shift registers.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] The data string is presented at "data in" and is shifted right one stage each time "data advance" is brought high.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] At each advance, the bit on the far left (i.e.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] "data in") is shifted into the first flip-flop's output.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] The data is stored after each on the "Q" output, so there are four storage "slots" available in this arrangement, hence it is a 4-bit register.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] To give an idea of the shifting pattern, imagine that the register holds 0000 (so all storage slots are empty).
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] As "data in" presents 1,0,1,1,0,0,0,0 (in that order, with a pulse at "data advance" each time—this is called clocking or strobing) to the register, this is the result.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] The right hand column corresponds to the right-most flip-flop's output pin, and so on.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] So the serial output of the entire value is 00010110.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] It can be seen that if data were to be continued to input, it would get exactly what was put in (10110000), but offset by four "data advance" cycles.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] This arrangement is the hardware equivalent of a queue.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] Also, at any time, the whole register can be set to zero by bringing the reset (R) pins high.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] This arrangement performs *destructive readout* – each datum is lost once it has been shifted out of the right-most bit.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] This configuration allows conversion from serial to parallel format.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] Data input is serial, as described in the SISO section above.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] Once the data has been clocked in, it may be either read off at each output simultaneously, or it can be shifted out.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] In this configuration, each flip-flop is edge triggered.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] All flip-flops operate at the given clock frequency.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] Each input bit makes its way down to the Nth output after N clock cycles, leading to parallel output.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] In cases where the parallel outputs should not change during the serial loading process, it's desirable to use a latched or buffered output.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] In a latched shift register (such as the 74595) the serial data is first loaded into an internal buffer register, then upon receipt of a load signal the state of the buffer register is copied into a set of output registers.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] In general, the practical application of the serial-in/parallel-out shift register is to convert data from serial format on a single wire to parallel format on multiple wires.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] This configuration has the data input on lines D1 through D4 in parallel format, D1 being the most significant bit.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] To write the data to the register, the Write/Shift control line must be held LOW.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] To shift the data, the W/S control line is brought HIGH and the registers are clocked.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] The arrangement now acts as a PISO shift register, with D1 as the Data Input.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] However, as long as the number of clock cycles is not more than the length of the data-string, the Data Output, Q, will be the parallel data read off in order.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] The animation below shows the write/shift sequence, including the internal state of the shift register.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] One of the most common uses of a shift register is to convert between serial and parallel interfaces.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] Serial-in serial-out shift registers can be used as simple delay circuits.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] Several bidirectional shift registers can also be connected in parallel for a hardware implementation of a stack.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] For more outputs, SIPO shift registers are used.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] The parallel outputs of the shift register and the desired state for all those devices can be sent out of the microcontroller using a single serial connection.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] For more inputs, PISO shift registers are used.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] Each binary input (such as a button or more complicated circuitry) is attached to a parallel input of the shift register, then the data is sent back serially to the microcontroller.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] Shift registers can also be used as pulse extenders.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] Compared to monostable multivibrators, the timing does not depend on component values, but it requires an external clock, and the timing accuracy is limited by the granularity of this clock.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] An example of such a pulse extender is the Ronja Twister, wherein five 74164 shift registers create the core of the timing logic this way (schematic).
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] Many computer languages include bitwise operations to "shift right" and "shift left" the data in a register, effectively dividing by two or multiplying by two for each place shifted.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] Very large serial-in serial-out shift registers (thousands of bits in size) were used in a similar manner to the earlier delay-line memory in some devices built in the early 1970s.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] Shift registers don't need many pins or address decoding logic, so was much cheaper than random-access memory back then.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] Such *shift register memory* was sometimes called *circulating memory*.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] Datapoint 3300, for example, stored its terminal display of 25 rows of 72 columns of 6-bit upper-case characters using 54 200-bit shift registers (arranged in 6 tracks of 9 packs), providing storage for 1800 characters.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] The shift register design meant that scrolling the terminal display could be accomplished by simply pausing the display output to skip one line of characters.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] A similar design was used for the Apple I's terminal.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] One of the first known examples of a shift register was in the Mark 2 Colossus, a code-breaking machine built in 1944.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] It was a six-stage device built of vacuum tubes and thyratrons.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] A shift register was also used in the IAS machine, built by John von Neumann and others at the Institute for Advanced Study in the late 1940s.
[src:gpio-expanders/shift-register] Shift registers made their way into integrated circuits in the 1960s as evidenced by early patents from Frank Wanlass and Kent Smith working at General Instrument.
